The key design decisions embedded in this:
The validate node runs every turn — not just at the start. Every time the graph mutates, the integrity rules re-evaluate. This means the assessments list is always current, and the interruption policy always has fresh signal to work with.
The integrate and mutate_graph nodes are separate intentionally. integrate processes human input and updates the ConversationState. mutate_graph applies changes to the KnowledgeGraph. Keeping them separate means you can validate a proposed mutation before committing it — which is exactly the "correctness over shortcuts" principle.
The router node has four exits — not two. continue loops back. complete means the conversation reached a natural conclusion. hand_off means the parent graph needs to take over (e.g., trigger a downstream artifact generation subgraph). error is explicit — no silent failures.
The loop-back arrow goes back to validate, not to the top of the graph. Every loop re-validates. The agent never assumes the graph is in a known state — it checks.
